article.description: Seimone Augustus had 15 points and six assists and Sylvia Fowles scored 16 points to lead No. 2 LSU to a 75-44 victory over Colorado in the championship game of the Coors Classic.
article.headline: Augustus in double figures for 33rd straight game
article.linkText: Augustus, LSU roll in Coors Classic title game
article.story:
BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- This time, LSU relied on its defense to
win its seventh straight game and a tournament championship.

Seimone Augustus had 15 points and six assists and Sylvia Fowles
scored 16 points to lead No. 2 LSU to a 75-44 victory over Colorado
in the final of the Coors Classic Saturday night.

Augustus finished 7-of-14 and scored in double figures for the
33rd straight game for LSU (7-0). The Tigers held Colorado to 24
percent shooting and without a basket for 13 minutes.

"It's just people's nature to look at offense, and defense is
not as glamorous," LSU coach Pokey Chatman said. "But it's always
been a staple for us and you can never have an off night on
defense."

Anna Nedovic led Colorado (2-2) with eight points. The Buffaloes
had 23 turnovers.

Colorado had a 30-minute closed-door meeting after the game.

"We had too many turnovers, and LSU's defense took us out of
our comfort zone," Buffaloes coach Ceal Barry said. "Their size,
speed and quickness was too much for us. In the second half, we
just lost our heart."

LSU used a pair of 7-0 runs and a late surge to lead 34-19 at
the half. Augustus, who had 15 points at the break, hit a short
jumper to put the Tigers up 17-7 and after Kara Richards scored for
Colorado, four different Tigers scored to extend the lead to 24-9.

Colorado went on a 7-0 run of its own while Augustus took a
short break and when Nedovic converted a three-point play, the
Buffaloes were within 26-18. Augustus returned and scored the next
six points.

"I'm not going to lie, I was intimidated coming into the
game," said Richards, who had six points and 10 rebounds. "But
once the game starts you just have to remember that (LSU) is
playing with the same rules as we are."

LSU stepped up its defensive pressure in the second half,
forcing six turnovers and holding Colorado without a point for
nearly eight minutes. Fowles scored four points during a 13-0 run
to extend the lead to 47-19 before Nedovic's free throw with 12:04
remaining.

"I think you saw that we did what we needed to win," Augustus
said. "We weren't happy with the way we played in the first and
stepped it up with our defense in the second half."

Colorado, which was held without a field goal over the final
5:13 of the first half, didn't convert another until 8:13 left in
the game on Nedovic's short jumper. By then the lead was 58-25 and
LSU was already resting its starters.
